## 9. Risks

| Risk | Impact | Mitigation |
|---|---|---|
| **AI-generated instructions are inaccurate or misleading** (wrong landmark, ambiguous phrasing) | High — safety-critical, could cause missed turns or accidents | Rigorous testing, conservative fallback to standard instructions, human review of instruction-generation prompts, real-world pilot testing before wide release |
| **Latency in AI instruction generation** during live navigation | High — delayed instructions are dangerous while driving | Pre-generate instructions per route upfront where possible; cache common landmark data; set strict latency SLAs with fallback |
| **Google Maps API cost at scale** | Medium — Directions/Places API usage costs scale with user growth | Monitor usage, implement caching for repeated routes, evaluate cost-tiering as usage grows |
| **Dependency on third-party APIs** (Google Maps, Firebase) | Medium — outages or policy/pricing changes affect core functionality | Abstract via Clean Architecture repository interfaces to allow provider swaps; monitor SLAs |
| **User trust/safety concerns with AI-generated guidance while driving** | High — regulatory and liability exposure | Clear disclaimers, conservative language generation, avoid ambiguous/creative phrasing in critical moments, extensive QA |
| **Landmark data staleness** (e.g., "the bakery" that closed) | Medium — reduces instruction accuracy over time | Combine multiple data sources (Places API) with freshness checks; allow user reporting/correction |
| **Privacy concerns** — location and trip history data | High — regulatory (GDPR/CCPA) and user trust risk | Clear privacy policy, data minimization, encryption at rest/in transit, user data deletion controls |
| **Competitive response** — Google/Waze could add similar natural-language features | Medium — erodes differentiation | Move fast on personalization/voice quality as a moat; consider B2B/API licensing as a parallel strategy |

